---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import TopicNext from '../../components/TopicNext.astro';
import MadeByKaj from '../../components/MadeByKaj.astro';
import TopicSkykitViewer from '../../components/TopicSkykitViewer.astro';

const title = 'White dwarfs: dead stars still glowing';
const summary = 'White dwarfs are the dense cooling remnants of ordinary stars and form a distinct faint branch in stellar-population plots.';
const nextTopics = [
	{ slug: 'hr-diagram', title: 'The Hertzsprung-Russell diagram' },
	{ slug: 'how-much-matter-can-we-actually-see', title: 'How much matter can we actually see?' }
];
---

<Layout title={`${title} | Learn | Found in Space`}>
	<SiteHeader section="Learn" />

	<main class="page">
		<article class="topic-content">
			<p class="eyebrow">Topic 11</p>
			<h1>{title}</h1>
			<p class="lede">{summary}</p>

			<section class="body">
				<p>
					When a star like our Sun runs out of fuel, it doesn't just disappear. Instead, it
					expels its outer layers (forming a planetary nebula) and leaves behind its
					extremely dense, hot core. This core is a white dwarf.
				</p>
				<p>
					White dwarfs are roughly the size of the Earth, but they have the mass of a full
					Sun. This means their density is almost unimaginable: a single teaspoon of
					white dwarf material would weigh as much as a mountain.
				</p>
				<p>
					Because they are no longer undergoing fusion, white dwarfs are essentially "dead"
					stars. They are simply cooling down over billions of years. In the nearby solar
					neighbourhood, many of the faintest objects we can detect are these cooling
					corpses of ancient stars.
				</p>

				<div class="callout panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">The Future of the Sun</p>
					<h3>Our Sun’s Ultimate Destiny</h3>
					<p>
						In about five billion years, our own Sun will become a white dwarf. It will
						slowly cool over many billions more years until it eventually becomes a cold,
						black dwarf—a fate it will share with most of the stars in the Milky Way.
					</p>
				</div>
			</section>

			<TopicSkykitViewer
				variant="neighbourhood"
				topic="white-dwarfs-dead-stars-still-glowing"
				highlight="white-dwarfs"
				showHr={true}
			/>

			<TopicNext topics={nextTopics} />
		</article>

		<MadeByKaj />
	</main>
</Layout>

<style>
	.page {
		max-width: 48rem;
		margin: 0 auto;
		padding: 3.2rem 1.5rem 5rem;
	}

	.topic-content {
		padding: 2rem 0;
	}

	.eyebrow {
		margin: 0 0 0.8rem;
		font-size: 0.8rem;
		letter-spacing: 0.16em;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		color: var(--fis-gold);
	}

	h1 {
		font-size: clamp(2.4rem, 6vw, 3.8rem);
		line-height: 1.05;
		margin: 0;
		font-weight: 600;
		letter-spacing: -0.03em;
	}

	.lede {
		margin-top: 1.5rem;
		font-size: 1.25rem;
		line-height: 1.7;
		color: var(--fis-text-soft);
	}

	.body {
		margin-top: 3rem;
	}

	.body p {
		font-size: 1.12rem;
		line-height: 1.8;
		color: var(--fis-text-soft);
		margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
	}

	.callout {
		margin: 3rem 0;
		padding: 2rem;
		background: var(--fis-panel);
		border: 1px solid var(--fis-line);
		border-radius: var(--fis-radius);
		backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
	}

	.callout h3 {
		margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
		font-size: 1.4rem;
		color: var(--fis-text);
	}

	.panel__eyebrow {
		margin: 0 0 0.8rem;
		font-size: 0.8rem;
		letter-spacing: 0.16em;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		color: var(--fis-gold);
	}
</style>
